  "title": "Operations on Radicals",
  "body": "Operations on Radicals  radical operations on  Products  radical multiplying  multiplying radicals  We have used the product rule for radicals, to simplify square roots. We can also use the product rule to multiply radicals together.  Product Rule  radical product rule   For example,  Find the product and simplify  First, we apply the product rule.   Which of these statements is correct:     (b) and (d)   We use the distributive law to remove parentheses from products involving radicals. Compare the product involving radicals on the left with the more familiar use of the distributive law on the right.  Multiply  Apply the distributive law to find   Explain why this statement is incorrect: Because is only one term.   In the next example, we use the distributive law along with the product rule to simplify the product.  Multiply  Apply the distributive law to obtain  Note the difference between the products The rule applies to the second product, but not the first.   Explain how to multiply . Multiply to get , multiply to get , write the product .   To multiply binomials, we use the FOIL method.  Multiply , then simplify.     Explain why . The square root of is a number that, when multiplied by itself, gives .    Quotients  We use the quotient rule to simplify square roots of fractions by writing . We can also use the quotient rule to simplify quotients of square roots.  Quotient Rule  radical quotient rule   Simplify  We use the quotient rule to write the expression as a single radical. Then we simplify the fraction inside the radical.   Is it true that we can only simplify a product or quotient of radicals if they are like radicals? No.    Fractions  fractions involving square roots  square root involving fractions  fractions involving square roots rationalizing the denominator  square root involving fractions rationalizing the denominator  When we solve quadratic equations, the solutions are often fractions that involve square roots. Many such fractions can be simplified using properties of radicals.  One of the solutions of the equation is . Simplify this radical expression.  First, simplify the square root: . Thus,  In , note that because and are not like terms. Also note that Because 8 is a term of the numerator, not a factor, we cannot cancel the 8's.   Which of these cannot be reduced: or ? Why? . The numerator cannot be factored.   We can add or subtract fractions involving radicals.  Subtract  The LCD for the two fractions is 6. We build each fraction to an equivalent one with denominator 6, then combine the numerators.   Rationalizing the Denominator  rationalizing the denominator  For some applications, it is easier to work with expressions that do not have radicals in the denominators of fractions. For example, the fraction is equivalent to We multiplied the numerator and denominator by , the same root that appeared in the denominator originally, and thus eliminated the radical from the denominator. This process is called rationalizing the denominator .  Rationalize the denominator of  We simplify the radical before attempting to rationalize the denominator. Now we multiply top and bottom of the fraction by .    What does it mean to rationalize the denominator? To eliminate radicals from the denominator.  What should you do before trying to rationalize a denominator?  Simplify the radicals.    Skills Warm-Up   Each simplification is incorrect. Give the correct simplification, or write c.b.s. if the expression cannot be simplified.            Answers to Skills Warm-Up   c.b.s.  c.b.s.  c.b.s.  c.b.s.        Activity 1: Products and Quotients   Find the product and simplify  Multiply  Multiply  Expand and simplify  Simplify    Activity 2: Fractions with Radicals   Add  Rationalize the denominator of    Activity 3: Application  In this Activity we use a formula for the surface area of a pyramid with a square base, as shown in the figure at right.  The pyramid has five faces, namely, the square base and four triangular sides. We know the height, , of the pyramid, and the length, , of the base.  pyramid  To calculate the surface area of the pyramid, we add the area of its base and the areas of the four triangular faces.  Use the formula given above to find the surface area of the Sun Pyramid in Mexico. The pyramid is 210 feet high and has a square base 689 feet on each side.  pyramid  Challenge: Can you verify the expression for the area of a triangular face of the pyramid? Begin by finding the altitude of the face.   Wrap-Up  Objectives  In this Lesson we practiced the following skills:  Simplifying products involving radicals  Simplifying quotients of radicals  Rationalizing the denominator  Questions   In Activity 1 Problem 5, why don't we start by rationalizing the denominator?  Explain why is not equivalent to .  In Activity 3, why don't we simplify to ?    Homework Preview   Find the product and simplify.       Find the quotient and simplify.     Subtract  Rationalize the denominator   Answers to Homework Preview             Homework 9.4  For Problems 1 3, simplify the product.      For Problems 4 6, multiply.      For Problems 7 10, multiply.       For Problems 11 13, simplify the quotient.  3     For Problems 14 16, reduce if possible.      For Problems 17 20, write the expression as a single fraction in simplest form.       For Problems 21 24, find and correct the error in the calculation.  Cannot be simplified      For Problems 25 28, rationalize the denominator.        Write an expression for the height of an equilateral triangle of side . (See the figure at right.)  Write an expression for the area of the triangle in part (a).    triangle         Write an expression in terms of for the height of the pyramid shown at right.  Write an expressionin terms of for the surface area of the pyramid.  pyramid  For Problems 31 33, verify by substitution that the given value is a solution of the equation.       "
